threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, no section header

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This ELF binary is a compact malicious stager or reverse shell, likely custom-written in assembly to minimize its footprint and avoid detection. It bypasses standard library calls by using direct Linux syscalls. Key malicious behaviors include: 1) Defining RWX (Read-Write-Execute) memory segments, which is a hallmark of self-modifying code or shellcode execution. 2) Utilizing 'sys_socket' (0x29) and 'sys_connect' (0x2a) to establish a TCP connection to a hardcoded remote peer. 3) Implementing a persistence loop using 'sys_nanosleep' (0x23) to retry the connection upon failure. 4) Executing a final 'jump' to a dynamically resolved memory address, indicating the execution of a second-stage payload received over the network.
